  "setup_detail": "<!--include:Pacing.TimedCampaigns-->\n\nOpening scene: open with the player already entangled in their chosen faction's world, seen from the inside — at the Marshal's war-table in the Arsenal, on the Exchange floor with someone's marker in hand, in a midnight office behind the Cathedral — caught up in the succession crisis as that faction experiences it, before they grasp the whole board. Establish the faction, its leader, and the pressure of the coronation clock. Do NOT reveal the throne's secret (the crucial-question) or the other factions' true natures yet. The player should begin partisan and certain, and learn later how little they saw.",
  "detail": "## The realm of Maredon\nMaredon is a three-century-old kingdom at the mouth of the river Maere, where the river meets the sea — and whoever holds that river-mouth holds the trade of half a continent. The realm was won by the sword, grown rich by the merchant houses who made its port the busiest on the coast, and crowned by the church that anointed its first king. Those three powers — the army, the coin, and the faith — are the three pillars Maredon stands on, and they are now the three factions tearing it apart.\n\nFor generations the crown passed cleanly. No longer. Crown Prince Caedran, the only heir, is dead — a hunting accident, the heralds say; a broken neck at the foot of a tower, the servants whisper; poison, the physicians will not say. Old King Halvard is dying (or has just died), with no other child and no named successor. Law and custom demand a crowned king before the season turns, and so the three pillars each advance a claim, and Maredon holds its breath.\n\nThe clocks (pick and run them): the coronation deadline the law demands; a foreign power eyeing the leaderless river-mouth and massing at the border; a plague stirring in the lower city. The coronation is the spine (see setup).\n\n## Vantis, the capital (location skeleton — grow more as the player moves)\nThe port-city climbs from the water up to the palace on the height, and each faction is seated somewhere in it. The bones:\n- **the harbor & the docks** — where the Compact's wealth flows in and out; the great chain that can close the river-mouth.\n- **the Exchange & the Customs House** — the Gilded Compact's seat; the ledgers that hold half the nobility's debts.\n- **the merchant quarter** — counting-houses and guild halls, the new money.\n- **the Arsenal & the barracks** — the Iron Circle's seat; the city garrison.\n- **the Cathedral precinct** — the Hallowed See's seat; where Maredon's kings are anointed, and nowhere else.\n- **the palace road** — the gated, watched climb up to the Adamant.\n- **the old town** — the original walled core and the old families who never forgave the new money.\n- **the foreign quarter** — envoys and exiles, and the eyes of the power at the border.\n- **the Reach** — the lower city; the poor, and the plague.\n- **the grand market** — where rumor moves faster than goods.\n- **the law courts & Gallows Square** — where the succession will be argued, and where it may end.\n- **the sea-wall & lighthouse** — the city's seaward face.\n- **the catacombs** — beneath all of it, older than the kingdom.\n\n## The Adamant, the palace (location skeleton — grow more as the player moves)\nThe fortress-palace crowning Vantis, and the seat of the crown:\n- **the Adamant Throne room** — and the throne itself (its true nature is the crucial-question's business).\n- **the great hall** — feasts, audiences, the public face of power.\n- **the council chamber** — where the three factions meet and fail to agree.\n- **Prince Caedran's apartments** — sealed since his death; the clues are in here.\n- **the King's sickroom** — old Halvard, dying or laid out; his last words, or the suspicious lack of them.\n- **the royal crypts** — the dead kings of Maredon, and whatever the throne has cost them.\n- **the guest wings** — each faction lodged under one roof, watching the others over dinner.\n- **the chapel royal** — the See's foothold inside the palace walls.\n- **the chancery & records vault** — the realm's paper; legitimacy lives and dies here.\n- **the undercroft kitchens** — where the servants are, and so where the gossip and the poison both move.\n- **the towers** — the astronomer's, and the prison's.\n- **the gardens** — the one place two enemies can speak and not be overheard.\n- **the question-rooms** — the dungeons; what the crown does when it stops being polite.\n\n## DM approach\n- All three factions have a sympathetic leader and an inner circle with its own agenda, and all three are equally complex. The player's starting faction (their fork) colors their first impression — but none of them is the 'good' one.\n- Start the player entangled with their chosen faction, inside its world, before they understand the full picture (see the opening pin). Reveal the second faction as nuanced allies-or-enemies by mid-campaign; the third faction's true nature is a late-game turn.\n- The throne's secret (the crucial-question) is the deep game beneath the politics — do not reveal it early.\n- Run the clocks: the coronation deadline above all, with the foreign army and the plague as mounting pressure the player reads in the city's mood.\n\nPacing: built around the coronation clock (see setup). Each faction's rising and falling fortunes, the foreign threat, and the plague are sub-clocks the player can track in the streets of Vantis.",
